times, although we will be talking about kings
and courts and aristocratic intrigue, but

00:00:25.339 --> 00:00:28.019
we're gonna be talking about all those things
in Japan.

00:00:36.720 --> 00:00:40.780
So discussions of Japanese history often focus
on the Tokugawa period because it's got ninja

00:00:40.790 --> 00:00:45.360
and samurai, but much of the foundation of
Japanese culture dates to the Heian period

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:48.520
between 782 and 1167 CE.

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:52.760
And when I say Japanese culture, I do mean
culture, because the achievements of the Heian

00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:57.640
period were primarily artistic, especially
in literature. So for most of this episode,

00:00:57.650 --> 00:01:01.840
we'll be looking at cultural history as opposed
to like economic or political history.

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:06.380
As a novelist, and also a consumer of culture,
I'm a big fan of cultural history. What I

00:01:06.380 --> 00:01:11.450
love about it is that it embraces the human
imagination. I mean, you can't just make up

00:01:11.450 --> 00:01:13.439
economic theories. Just kidding, you can.

00:01:13.439 --> 00:01:17.710
Anyway, for our purposes, Heian culture is
the high culture of the upper-upper-class

00:01:17.710 --> 00:01:22.780
aristocracy, and obviously focusing on this
tiny sliver of the upper class leaves out

00:01:22.780 --> 00:01:26.770
the experience of most Japanese people. But
we know a lot more about the elite than we

00:01:26.770 --> 00:01:31.170
know about everyone else because it was the
elite who were doing all of the writing things

00:01:31.170 --> 00:01:35.170
down and they were writing about the people
they found the most interesting - themselves.

00:01:35.170 --> 00:01:38.319
In fact one of the reasons we know a great
deal about the Heian aristocracy is because

00:01:38.319 --> 00:01:43.619
of Japan's first great novel: The Tale of
the Genji, by Lady Murasaki Shikibu. Now the

00:01:43.619 --> 00:01:46.039
historian James Murdoch called the Heian aristocracy

00:01:46.039 --> 00:01:51.880
"An ever-pullulating brood of greedy, needy,
frivolous dilletanti - as often as not foully

00:01:51.880 --> 00:01:55.980
licentious, utterly effeminate, incapable
of any worthy achievement".

00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:59.700
But when you boil all the unnecessarily fancy
words out of that quote, that sounds like

00:01:59.700 --> 00:02:03.939
people I'm very interested in learning about.
In fact, I love some fallicentuousness.

00:02:03.939 --> 00:02:08.780
So one of the first things we learn from texts
about the Heian aristocracy is that the aristocracy

00:02:08.780 --> 00:02:14.010
was dominated by a craze for things Chinese.
Now Chinese visitors to Japan thought the

00:02:14.010 --> 00:02:17.209
country was backwards and out of the way and
uncivilized.

00:02:17.209 --> 00:02:21.269
But one of the reasons the Japanese seemed
backwards to Chinese visitors is that the

00:02:21.269 --> 00:02:25.470
Japanese in the 10th century admired Tang
China, which had flourished a couple of hundred

00:02:25.470 --> 00:02:29.640
years earlier. But there was also the fact
that the Japanese blended Chinese ideas, especially

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:32.209
Chinese Buddhism, with native traditions.

00:02:32.209 --> 00:02:36.340
In fact one of the most interesting aspects
of Heian Japan was the overall attitude of

00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:41.280
the aristocracy, which was characterized by
a love of color, and grandeur, and ceremony,

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:46.299
and ritual, that was tinged with some Buddhist-inspired
ideas. You know, it's sort of like how everyone

00:02:46.299 --> 00:02:50.970
in Canada wears powdered wigs and knee breeches
to look like 18th century England.

00:02:50.970 --> 00:02:55.129
And one of the central ideas in Buddhism is
that everything beautiful, and also everything

00:02:55.129 --> 00:02:59.430
not beautiful, is fleeting. Like historian
Ivan Morris wrote that in the literature of

00:02:59.430 --> 00:03:03.719
the time, there was a quote "feeling that
the familiar order of things will soon come

00:03:03.719 --> 00:03:07.370
to an end." Which by the way is always an
appropriate feeling.

00:03:07.370 --> 00:03:12.200
So the center of aristocratic court life was
the capital, Heian Jyo, which during the Heian

00:03:12.200 --> 00:03:17.349
golden age may have had a populations as high
as 100,000 people, making it much larger than

00:03:17.349 --> 00:03:20.849
most European cities at the time. It may have
been a glorious capital but we don’t really

00:03:20.849 --> 00:03:25.369
know because most of the city was destroyed
by earthquakes, or possibly fires, or possibly

00:03:25.369 --> 00:03:28.640
wars, or just the desire for new construction.
We're not sure.

00:03:28.650 --> 00:03:33.200
We also know that the Heian aristocracy was
rigidly hierarchical, with society divided

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:38.430
into about 30 grades based on one's birth.
The top 4 grades were reserved for princes,

00:03:38.430 --> 00:03:43.510
and the top 3, known as the Kugyō, received
all the most important privileges, including

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:46.920
governmental posts and revenues from special
rice land.

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:50.760
These people in the highest ranks could send
their children to university, wear ceremonial

00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:54.640
dress, they were given lighter punishments
when they committed crimes. Can you imagine

00:03:54.650 --> 00:03:59.569
a world in which rich people systemically
receive lighter sentences for crimes committed

00:03:59.569 --> 00:04:00.609
than poor people?

00:04:00.609 --> 00:04:04.469
These rules were so detailed that they even
determined what type of fan you could hold.

00:04:04.469 --> 00:04:07.560
The top 3 ranks got to hold 25-fold fans.

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:11.459
But when The Tale of the Genji was written,
this rank system, like all those ranks, applied

00:04:11.459 --> 00:04:18.090
to less than 1/10th of 1% of the total population,
so we’re really talking about the elites.

00:04:18.090 --> 00:04:19.109
As Ivan Morris put it:

00:04:19.109 --> 00:04:23.590
"Members of the upper class are almost all
related to each other. They are totally uninterested

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:28.530
in everyone outside their charmed circle and
exceedingly sensitive in judging the precise

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:33.590
social level of each person who does belong.
In Murasaki's milieu, to determine a person's

00:04:33.590 --> 00:04:38.009
milieu was no simple diversion, but a matter
of overriding importance."

00:04:38.009 --> 00:04:41.520
Now that description reminds me a lot of my
high school experience.

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:45.220
Aristocrats dominated the government, which
over time became more and more ceremonial

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:49.639
and ritualistic. In fact by the 10th century,
much government work was carried out at night

00:04:49.639 --> 00:04:54.430
and consisted almost entirely of ceremonies.
The nice thing about doing boring ceremonial

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:56.500
work at night though: there was a lot of wine.

00:04:56.500 --> 00:05:00.360
So yeah, that doesn't make for like, excellent
government efficiency. Heian Japan's economy

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:05.550
was not much better than its governance. There
was very little trade and attempted land reform,

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:10.050
which was supposed to grant every citizen
a parcel of public domain land, totally failed.

00:05:10.050 --> 00:05:15.080
Meanwhile, aristocrats accumulated vast agricultural
land holdings, and by the 10th century court

00:05:15.080 --> 00:05:20.120
nobles were largely supported by these tax-free
estates called manors. Now interestingly,

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:25.330
the nobles didn't technically own the land
outright, as they did in much of Europe. Instead

00:05:25.330 --> 00:05:29.800
they owned the rights to income from the land
and then those rights could be transferred

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:33.360
to their heirs, so it was similar to ownership,
but it wasn't quite ownership.

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:37.820
Also different from Europe: upper-class Japanese
women could hold the rights to a manor, and

00:05:37.830 --> 00:05:42.020
thus have a rather impressive degree of economic
power. And that matters a lot because women

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:46.270
played a key role in the flourishing of Heian
literary culture that makes this period of

00:05:46.270 --> 00:05:48.819
history so interesting to study in the first
place.

00:05:48.819 --> 00:05:53.819
Like over all this inefficient corrupt cronyism
of Japan's government and economy definitely

00:05:53.819 --> 00:05:58.720
weakened this state. But it also provided
time and money for the aristocracy to make

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:01.060
beautiful and interesting things.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:05.550
Let's go to the Thought Bubble. Heian aristocrats
were expected to feel melancholy over the

00:06:05.550 --> 00:06:06.980
transience of existence.

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:11.580
"In Murasaki's time," according to Ivan Morris
"periodical protestations of melancholy and

00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:16.580
gloom were essential for people who regarded
themselves as sensitive," and sensitivity

00:06:16.580 --> 00:06:21.879
especially to art was the hallmark of aristocratic
breeding. The aristocratic gentleman is exemplified

00:06:21.879 --> 00:06:26.960
by prince Genji himself: quote "With his gentle
nature, his sensitivity and his wide range

00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:32.250
of artistic skills, who represented the ideal
of the age and who set the tone for the social

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:34.539
and cultural life of the good people"

00:06:34.539 --> 00:06:39.680
Buddhism was very influential on the aristocrats
aesthetic ideal that beauty must be cultivated

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:44.240
because it is so impermanent. This quote from
the tale of Genji illustrates this focus on

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:49.220
impermanence: "'Like the waterfowl that play
there on the lake, I too am floating along

00:06:49.220 --> 00:06:54.129
the surface of a transient world' I could
not help comparing them with myself. For they

00:06:54.129 --> 00:06:58.830
too appeared to be enjoying themselves in
the most carefree fashion; yet their lives

00:06:58.830 --> 00:06:59.940
must be full of sorrow."

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:03.310
Stan, are you sure that's from the tale of
Genji? I think I've seen that quote attributed

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:07.810
to me on Tumblr. But we don't only know about
the emotional state of the aristocracy, we

00:07:07.810 --> 00:07:13.009
also know about their pastimes. We refer to
nobles as the leisure class for a reason after

00:07:13.009 --> 00:07:16.940
all, they spent a lot of time playing games,
and engaging in contests.

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:20.979
Poetry contests were popular, as were board
games, like Go, and much of their time was

00:07:20.979 --> 00:07:23.229
taken up with ceremonies and rituals.

