00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:53.500
from the cup of defeat.

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:59.599
So you know other than pure Game of Thrones
style drama, this highly ritualized very insular

00:07:59.599 --> 00:08:03.359
social order of the elites of the elites of
the elites isn't usually the kind of stuff

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:04.760
we'd study at Crash Course.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:07.360
But first, thinking about the lives of the
Heian aristocracy tells us something about

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:11.729
the lives of the rich and powerful generally.
Like obviously they had to increasingly separate

00:08:11.729 --> 00:08:15.849
themselves from each other to feel more and
more wealthy and powerful.

00:08:15.849 --> 00:08:20.470
Which progressively led to them being more
and more separated from, you know, the vast,

00:08:20.470 --> 00:08:25.669
vast majority of people living in Japan. But
also they produced and consumed cultural artifacts

00:08:25.669 --> 00:08:30.590
that came to define the style of the age but
also have continued to shape culture.

00:08:30.590 --> 00:08:35.940
Heian aristocracy and the documents that describe
it tell us a lot about women, who as we've

00:08:35.940 --> 00:08:40.669
seen are often left out of historical narratives.
The Heian period, at least culturally, was

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:44.930
dominated by women, particularly Murasaki
Shikibu and Sei Shōnagon.

00:08:44.930 --> 00:08:49.540
So in some ways at least, unlike almost everything
we've studied, our view of the period is dominated

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:54.160
by women's perspectives, although it is the
perspective of the most privileged women.

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:58.320
And what we see is consistent with a lot of
upper-class mores: these women are obsessed

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:02.010
with their looks, and especially with their
clothes which were cumbersome and heavy. They

00:09:02.010 --> 00:09:06.390
were expected to wear their hair very long,
preferably reaching to the ground. They had

00:09:06.390 --> 00:09:11.560
to powder their faces and blacken their teeth
and they lived the circumscribed lives typical

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:13.779
of upper-class women throughout the world.

00:09:13.779 --> 00:09:17.290
Although there were some legal protections
that they enjoyed: like we talked about how

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:21.170
they could have income from property. Laws
also protected them from physical violence,

00:09:21.170 --> 00:09:25.430
specifically prohibiting a husband from beating
his wife, which might not sound like that

00:09:25.430 --> 00:09:29.470
big of a deal but compared to women's lives
in Europe, that was a big improvement.

00:09:29.470 --> 00:09:33.380
And upper-class women in Heian Japan were
all literate and educated, although their

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:37.730
education was limited to the types of cultural
skills that would make them attractive to

00:09:37.730 --> 00:09:43.160
men: poetry, music, calligraphy, maybe some
literature. Disciplines like history and law

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:45.510
and philosophy were mostly off limits.

00:09:45.510 --> 00:09:48.519
And that brings me to something I want to
talk about: all of these privileges: from

00:09:48.519 --> 00:09:53.110
the heavy, cumbersome clothes that make it
difficult to move to the kinds of education

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:57.730
women could have or the kinds of limited legal
protections they could have, all of that is

00:09:57.730 --> 00:09:59.339
evidence of a patriarchy.

00:09:59.339 --> 00:10:03.100
So we see through these women's stories the
way that they were able to express themselves

00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:07.529
and their philosophies and the way that they
lived in the world. So women like Murasaki

00:10:07.529 --> 00:10:11.740
Shikibu lived constrained, cloistered lives,
but of course there were opportunities available

00:10:11.740 --> 00:10:15.029
to them that weren't available to men. And
that's what's so exciting about being able

00:10:15.029 --> 00:10:19.560
to read their narratives. We just don't have
many equivalents to that in Europe at the time.

00:10:19.560 --> 00:10:24.580
That noted, these women, like their male counterparts,
spent most of their lives indoors, and communicated

00:10:24.589 --> 00:10:29.870
mostly by intermediaries or letters. Women
couldn't show themselves to men or make conversation

00:10:29.870 --> 00:10:34.120
with them. But there was a great deal of interest
and intrigue around love and romance, not

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:39.420
least because Heian gentlemen were expected to be
polygamous and also to engage in extramarital affairs.

00:10:39.420 --> 00:10:43.400
But just because sexual relations were often
divorced from marriage and love affairs were

00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:47.860
common doesn't mean that they lacked emotional
consequences. In the stories you read about

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:53.170
Heian Japan everybody is always worried that
they're going to like, fall out of favor with

00:10:53.170 --> 00:10:59.019
their lover or their husband or their whatever.
It's so exciting! To read about, I mean, I'm

00:10:59.019 --> 00:11:01.359
sure if you're living inside of it it would
make you very anxious.

00:11:01.360 --> 00:11:06.280
Also when courtship and marriage had political
dimensions, as they did in the highest noble

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:11.200
ranks, women were often in danger of being
displaced by a more advantageous match.

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:15.370
And we know from the stories that all of this
combined into pangs of jealousy and fear of

00:11:15.370 --> 00:11:19.720
being abandoned and then pain when you actually
were abandoned. And those kinds of stories,

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:23.040
I'm sure I don't have to tell you, have a
kind of universality about them.

00:11:23.040 --> 00:11:26.660
The last thing I want to say here is that
power works differently when you're not in

00:11:26.660 --> 00:11:29.520
power, right? Like if you're a student in
a high school classroom the teacher has the

00:11:29.529 --> 00:11:31.620
power, but you have some power.

00:11:31.620 --> 00:11:36.000
And the most interesting thing about the stories
from the Heian aristocracy is the ways that women

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:41.860
used the power that they did have to bring about
change in their own lives and in their communities.

00:11:41.860 --> 00:11:45.820
So by looking at history through the lens
of literature we get a very different perspective

00:11:45.829 --> 00:11:50.779
than if we were to focus on government documents,
or archaeology, or descriptions of war. This

00:11:50.779 --> 00:11:55.350
helps us to try to develop a sense of how
people at the time felt, although we're only

00:11:55.350 --> 00:11:57.970
dealing with a very limited group of people,
obviously.

00:11:57.970 --> 00:12:02.550
The cultural achievements of the Heian Period,
described and exemplified by The Tale of Genji,

00:12:02.550 --> 00:12:06.699
were considerable, especially when compared
to what Europeans were accomplishing at the

00:12:06.699 --> 00:12:10.359
time. And it's another reminder that we need
to be careful when we talk about the 9th and

00:12:10.360 --> 00:12:12.680
10th centuries as the Dark Ages.

00:12:12.680 --> 00:12:16.500
It's also interesting that the Heian Period
in Japan wasn't particularly successful politically

00:12:16.500 --> 00:12:21.699
or economically, but that it did lead to great
cultural achievements. And almost all of the

00:12:21.699 --> 00:12:26.110
literary achievements were made by women,
which as Morris points out is "a rare, if

00:12:26.110 --> 00:12:28.620
not unique, phenomenon in cultural history."

00:12:28.620 --> 00:12:32.820
For Heian Japan the historical record was
written primarily by women. And while The

00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:36.459
Tale of Genji doesn't discuss politics or
economics the way that we usually imagine

00:12:36.459 --> 00:12:41.220
them, and while it describes a world that
leaves out 99% of Japanese people during the

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:44.949
period, it has a lot to tell us about the
way that at least some people felt and lived,

00:12:44.949 --> 00:12:47.310
which is more than can be said for a lot of
history books.

00:12:47.310 --> 00:12:51.329
And that's a type of history that most of
us can relate to more than stuff with generals

00:12:51.329 --> 00:12:55.149
and kings in it. For instance when I look
at the history of my own life I find that

00:12:55.149 --> 00:13:01.289
generals and kings have played a very minor
role. Jealously on the other hand: not insignificant.

